metadata.name: Cloverfield #243
metadata.description:
"Nature is the source of all true knowledge".

Have you ever taken the time to look, deeply look, at all the details in a humble patch of grass ?

In this tiny microcosm, a constant, fierce battle is going on, day after day, plants reaching out for sun, down for access to soil, fighting for survival. Smaller grasses form groups, alliances making it harder for taller ones to take over. Dead leaves remind us that some of them lost the fight, fallen warriors who, soon enough, will be forgotten too. Growth, decay, life, death, the endless cycle, right in front of our eyes.

It is fascinating, and, for me at least, an endless source of inspiration.

It is my hope that, through this project, you will take the time to take a closer look at nature, and that, as the pale blue dot we call home keeps getting drier and drier, remember that even humble patches of grass should not be taken for granted.


Key commands:
's' - save as png
'b' - make the background transparent (for printing)
'1', '2, '4' - set the pixel density, for resolutions up to 8000x8000

This updated version of the project should render on mobile devices, albeit with slightly reduced quality. 
If you want to save the image for printing, I recommend you do so on desktop.

metadata.name: Accalance 2 #3
metadata.description:
This work is an artistic investigation into the visual weight of colors and based on preliminary research results: Each piece in this series is based on an analogous color harmony and displays a range of hues arranged around a single primary color, while the balancing algorithm varies the forms and the area coverage of the color fields and their respective brightness (keeping saturation constant) to keep the whole composition in perfect visual balance.

In terms of color scheme, typography and design, the work is inspired by the International Typographic Style movement (Swiss Style), which was characterized by clarity, openness, a desire for democracy, a highly intellectual approach and the credo that design - and the designer himself - should take a "backseat" in the creation and even become "invisible". All of this, I believe, is also a very fitting description of the generative art scene.

The primary color in each piece is denoted by one out of 24 different color tables (some rarer than others), which cover the full 360Â° degree range of hues. Furthermore, there are three different grid sizes (3x3, 4x4 and 5x5), two positions for the typography (top and bottom) and four different paper stocks (coated cool white, uncoated cool while, uncoated warm white and newspaper).

The token is rendered in high resolution (4800x6000px) in the background, which allows for saving and printing in high quality up to a height of about 20" (50cm).

Mouse Interactions:

It is possible to experiment with the hue range of the color scheme and the overall saturation of the artwork without changing the visual balance: Simply hover the mouse next to the bars that are titled "HUE RANGE" and "SATURATION" and use the mouse wheel (or the fingers on the touch pad) to increase or decrease the values. Pressing 'r' resets both values back to their original state.

Keys enabled for this token:

r: Resets hue range and saturation to the initial values.
m: Toggles the margins on and off.
d: Outputs a description of the features in the console.
s: Saves the artwork in high-resolution (4800x6000px).
c: Displays the copyright notice.

metadata.name: Redundancy #24
metadata.description:
This generative token explores redundancy as an architectural concept, method, and process. Redundancy provides flexibility in an open form, enabling a shift from monofunctional to multifunctional as well as from optimized to resilient. A hybrid architecture in which complexity is created through the continuous reconfiguration of simple discrete and compatible blocks.
Each minted redundancy token reveals various deterministic rare features, styles, and scales, creating endlessly redundant open architectures. 

Redundancy Generative Token by @grasser_alex 2022

metadata.name: Obliques #96
metadata.description:
Obliques are a reinterpretation of Parallels, a collection of AI generated color fields by Marc Maurer. Many of the pieces in that collection are CC0, which basically means they can be reused for other projects, like this one.

Obliques takes artifacts from Parallels and uses them as brushes, painting slices of the original image on the canvas in a (hopefully) pleasant, chaotic way.

About 10% will be "Glitched".

The "Source Material" property will tell you the name of piece that it is using.

You can see Marc Maurer's Parallels project here:
https://objkt.com/collection/KT1TiSEcASGD19SW8bmqrqgSgCBkwXqDdTJ1

Obliques are also CC0, so feel free use anything here in other projects.

You can read more about CC0 here:
https://creativecommons.org/share-your-work/public-domain/cc0/

G : Toggle Grain
M : Toggle Matte
S : Save Image
1 -> 6 : Set pixel density
(Default pixel density is 1 @ 2000x2000)

objkt.name: M'Fing Dots on a M'Fing Grid #144

metadata.name: M'Fing Dots on a M'Fing Grid #144
metadata.description:
M'Fing Dots on a M'Fing Grid was an fxhash speedrun any% < 720 minutes project. Started at 10:30am Fri 5th August 2022, and finished at 10:30pm Fri 5th August 2022.

The repo for the code base can be found at: https://github.com/revdancatt/mfing-dots-on-a-mfing-grid - progress of writing code over the 12 hours can be seen in the commit history.

## THE PROJECT

The idea behind the project was to take one of the simplest things in generative art, randomly coloured dots on a grid.

Many projects use dots on a grid as the base foundation for building more complexity. However, just the dots themselves are often considered too simple to have as a project on their own.

Given the limited amount of time for a 12-hour speed run, I decided to see if I could take something as simple as dots and inject just a little bit of GenArt personality into it. Adding textures, variations and controlled colour selection.

It's about as simple you can get with dots on a grid, without being simple. This is my [speed run] version, show me yours.

## SPEED RUN

The tradition of doing a "speed run" on fxhash was started by Alexis AndrÃ© (@MacTuitui) and his "fxhash SpeedRun: any% < 960 minutes" project (#11995), described as "A performance piece. From cloning the template to a decent piece in less than 960 minutes".

Two more speed run collections have been created "Consequence Broadcast" (#13359) and "Beacon" (#17542) both by Amy Goodchild.

This is a fxhash speedrun any% < 720 run.

The any% is from game speed running and means "to get to the end with any % finished", meaning you don't have to 100% complete the game, just get to the end credits. For a gen art project it means you can use libraries and copy bits and bobs from your previous code, without having to do everything from scratch.

< 720 means that it's done in less than 720 minutes, in this case 12 hours.

metadata.name: PolyGarden #281
metadata.description:
Polygons, patterns and flowers are mixtured in my garden. I start with a birdeye view of the garden and its geometric structure. The species diversity and the random stack of rocks, sands, fences and other objects are main structures I want to capture, in an abstract and planar style. 

Moreover, in this project, I also try to explore the representation ability of generative art. I select three elements: shape of entity, layout of palette, and stack of object location. The factors behind these elements are the balance of randomness and structure: the generative art generates the variants from randomness but restricts its chaos with structure (deterministic constraints) to represent the meaningful results. 

Variables:
- 4 layouts
- 6 texture patterns
- 15 color palette
- 3 randomness
- 2 completeness

Please be patient with drawing process.
